Hospice and Palliative Care: An Overview.

Tatum PE(1), Mills SS(2).

Author information:
(1)Dell Medical School, University of Texas in Austin, 1501 Red River Street, 
Austin, TX 78701, USA. Electronic address: Paul.Tatum@austin.utexas.edu.
(2)Dell Medical School, University of Texas in Austin, 1501 Red River Street, 
Austin, TX 78701, USA.

Palliative medicine is specialized medical care for people with serious illness. 
Serious illness is one with high risk of mortality that negatively affects 
quality of life or function or is burdensome in symptoms, treatments, or 
caregiver stress. Palliative care improves symptom management and addresses the 
needs of patients and families, resulting in improved patient and caregiver 
quality of life and reduced symptom burden and health care utilization. Hospice 
is palliative care for patients with a prognosis of 6 months or less and is 
appropriate when goals are to avoid hospitalization and maximize time at home 
for patients who are dying.

