Prognostication in Serious Illness.

Martin EJ(1), Widera E(2).

Author information:
(1)Division of General Internal Medicine and Health Services Research, 
Department of Medicine, University of California, Los Angeles, 757 Westwood 
Plaza Suite 7501, Los Angeles, CA 90095, USA. Electronic address: 
ejmartin@mednet.ucla.edu.
(2)Division of Geriatrics, Department of Medicine, University of California, San 
Francisco, San Francisco, CA, USA; San Francisco Veterans Affairs Health Care 
System, 4150 Clement Street, Box 181G, San Francisco, CA 94121, USA. Electronic 
address: https://twitter.com/EWidera.

Prognostication is a vital aspect of decision making because it provides 
patients and families with information to establish realistic and achievable 
goals of care, is used in determining eligibility for certain benefits, and 
helps in targeting interventions to those likely to benefit. Prognostication 
consists of 3 components: clinicians use their clinical judgment or other tools 
to estimate the probability of an individual developing a particular outcome 
over a specific period of time; this prognostic estimate is communicated in 
accordance with the patient's information preferences; the prognostic estimate 
is interpreted by the patient or surrogate and used in clinical decision making.

